==Areas of management application==
Management application can be utilised by a person or a group of persons and by a company or a group of companies depending upon the type of management skills being used.  Management can be applied to every aspect of activity of a person or an organization:

=== Self-management skills ===

[[Self-governance]] is the act of conducting oneself to get things done.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Drucker |first1=Peter |date=March–April 1999 |title=''Managing Oneself'' |url=https://hbr.org |journal=''[[Harvard Business Review]]''}}</ref> Effective management of oneself is a natural prerequisite of effective management.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inc.com/rhett-power/manage-yourself-first-then-you-can-effectively-manage-others.html |title=Manage yourself first, then you can effectively manage others |last=Power |first=Rhett |date=September 3, 2014 |publisher=''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]'' |access-date=July 9, 2017 |quote="If you can't manage your own life, how can you expect to manage other people?"}}</ref> Personal skills related to business activity include:
* [[Managerial effectiveness]] &ndash; ''getting the right things done''. [[Peter Drucker]] reminds us that "effectiveness ''can'' and ''must'' be learned".<ref>Peter F. Drucker (2006). ''The Effective Executive: The Definitive Guide to Getting the Right Things Done''. New York: Collins.</ref>
* Self-control &ndash; in the general sense, controlling one's own actions and states
** [[Attention management]] &ndash; 
** [[Stress management]] &ndash; 
** [[Task management]] &ndash; 
** [[Time management]] &ndash; 
* [[Self-employment]] &ndash; 
* Personal resource management
** [[Personal information management]] &ndash; 
** [[Personal knowledge management]] &ndash; 
** [[Personal finance]]

