{{Infobox officeholder
|name        = Pam Pollard
|office      = Chair of the [[Oklahoma Republican Party]]
|term_start  = October 11, 2015
|term_end    = 
|predecessor = [[Estela Hernandez]] {{small|(Acting)}}
|successor   = 
|birth_date  = 
|birth_place = 
|death_date  = 
|death_place = 
|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]
|education   = [[University of Florida]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br>[[East Central University|East Central University, Ada]]<br>{{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}
}}
'''Pam Pollard''' is the current chair of the [[Republican Party of Oklahoma]]. She has previously served as the Vice Chair of the Republican party of Oklahoma, and the President of the Oklahoma Federation of Republican Women. She is the owner and President of Pollard Accounting and Tax Service.

As state Chairwoman, Pollard was a delegate to the [[2016 Republican National Convention]], but she was not bound to a predetermined candidate.<ref name="DenwaltConvention">{{cite news|last1=Denwalt|first1=Dale|title=Party time: State's prospective GOP delegates look ahead to convention|url=https://search.proquest.com/news/docview/1778319566/fulltext/A3F496A98ABE493CPQ/49?accountid=10226|accessdate=12 December 2017|publisher=[[The Journal Record]]|date=30 March 2016}}</ref>  She was among the handful of unbound delegates nationwide who publicly announced support for Donald Trump before the July 18 Convention, enabling Trump to clinch the nomination on May 26, 2016.<ref name="Ohlemacher">{{cite news|last1=Ohlemacher|first1=Stephen|title=Over the top: Trump sews up delegates to seal GOP nomination|url=https://search.proquest.com/news/docview/1792284629/fulltext/2A02A1E996434B2BPQ/26?accountid=10226|accessdate=12 December 2017|publisher=St. Louis Post - Dispatch|date=27 May 2016}}</ref><ref name="BlanchardYikes"/>  She told the Associated Press, "I think he has touched a part of our electorate that doesn't like where our country is... I have no problem supporting Mr. Trump."<ref name="Ohlemacher"/>  British political reporter Jack Blanchard described Pollard as "divisive".<ref name="BlanchardYikes">{{cite news|last1=Blanchard|first1=Jack|title=YIKES! TRUMP GETS THE NOD: Now unstoppable as key votes secured|url=https://search.proquest.com/news/docview/1791537271/fulltext/A3F496A98ABE493CPQ/50?accountid=10226|accessdate=12 December 2017|publisher=Daily Mirror|date=27 May 2016}}</ref>

Pollard was an enthusiastic supporter of [[Sarah Palin]] in 2008.<ref name="HarndenThatcher">{{cite news|last1=Harnden|first1=Tony|title=Delegates hail Palin as the new Thatcher|url=https://search.proquest.com/news/docview/321623486/fulltext/A3F496A98ABE493CPQ/55?accountid=10226|accessdate=12 December 2017|publisher=London Daily Telegraph|date=5 September 2008}}</ref>  

== Education ==
Pollard graduated from the [[University of Florida]] with a degree in Forest Engineering.{{cn|date=December 2017}} Later she returned to school and earned a B.A in Accounting from [[East Central University]].{{cn|date=December 2017}}

== Career ==
Pollard worked in small business accounting and tax preparation for over 27 years.<ref name="FortySix News">{{Cite news |author=Clements, Mike |title=A Look at Pam Pollard and Why She Seeks to be the Next Chairman of the OKGOP |work=FortySix News |date=October 8, 2015 |url=http://fortysixnews.com/stories/2015/10/08/a-look-at-pam-pollard-and-why-she-seeks-to-be-the-next-chairman-of-the-okgop/ |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref>

Pollard served on the Board of Directors for [[The Hugs Project]]. In 2004 she served as the coordinator for the 72 hour "Get Out The Vote" program for the Republican Party of Oklahoma.{{cn|date=December 2017}} Later, in 2005 she took a job as an office manager and scheduler for Congressman [[Ernest Istook|Ernest Istook's]] [[Oklahoma gubernatorial election, 2006|2006 gubernatorial campaign]]. Later that year she became the state treasurer for the Oklahoma Federation of Republican Women.{{cn|date=December 2017}}

In 2007, Pollard was elected as the chair of the [[Oklahoma County, Oklahoma|Oklahoma County Republican Party]] and became the assistant state director with [[Americans for Prosperity]].{{cn|date=December 2017}} In 2010 she worked with [[Mary Fallin]]'s gubernatorial campaign.{{cn|date=December 2017}}

Pollard was elected President of the Oklahoma Federation of Republican Woman in 2014.{{cn|date=December 2017}} Later, in 2015, Pollard campaigned for Chair of the Oklahoma Republican Party. She lost the election to [[Randy Brogdon]] but after Brogdon resigned, she was elected.<ref name="The Oklahoman">{{Cite news |author=Dinger, Matt |title=Oklahoma Republican Party chooses new chairman |newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]] |date=October 12, 2015 |url=http://newsok.com/article/5452928 |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref>

