{{SLA|Finland|16|15|2010|Citizens must complete comprehensive school. The age of finishing it varies depending on the age of starting school (mostly 7) and years held back. Most graduate from comprehensive school at the age of 16. Pupils who have not finished comprehensive school by the age of 17 (which is marginal) may quit school. Post-secondary (tertiary) education is voluntary.}}
{{SLA|France|16|16|2010|The statutory minimum school leaving age is 16. There are, however, a few specific cases where young people may enter employment before the age of 16, such as employment in the parents' company, sporadic work, or young people who have left school early taking up an [[apprenticeship]] at 15, to name a few.<ref>[http://www.eurofound.europa.eu/eiro/2005/12/tfeature/fr0512101t.html Contribution to EIRO thematic feature on Youth and work - case of France<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120802125255/http://www.eurofound.europa.eu/eiro/2005/12/tfeature/fr0512101t.html |date=2012-08-02 }}</ref>}}
{{SLA|Germany|18|(15)|2003|The statutory minimum school leaving age is essentially set at 18.<ref>[http://www.onlineopinion.com.au/view.asp?article=217"School: leaving it too early" - by Andrew Leigh] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103044746/http://www.onlineopinion.com.au/view.asp?article=217 |date=2014-01-03 }}</ref> The federal ''Jugendarbeitsschutzgesetz'' (Youth Employment Protection Act) regulates the minimum employment age, which is set at 15.<ref>[http://bundesrecht.juris.de/jarbschg/index.html  Text of the German Youth Employment Protection Act in German], provided by the German [[Federal Ministry of Justice (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Justice]].</ref> However, from the person's 15th to their 18th birthday, they are obliged by [[States of Germany|state]] law to pursue at least part-time [[Vocational education|vocational]] secondary education, usually within the German [[dual education system]]. Some germans students leaving school at 17 and 6 months}}
{{SLA|Greece|15|15|2011|}}
