{{SLA|Netherlands|18|13|2014|Education is compulsory from the age of 5 to 18. Secondary education is divided in several levels, with [[Voorbereidend middelbaar beroepsonderwijs|vmbo]] students typically graduating at age 16, [[hoger algemeen voortgezet onderwijs|havo]] students at 17 and [[voorbereidend wetenschappelijk onderwijs|vwo]] students at 18. After obtaining a havo or vwo diploma, the student is no longer obligated to go to school regardless of their age. Except those students which have done vmbo, they must have a mbo level 2 or higher diploma before quitting school.

Also, all children between those ages, even if they're refugees or new, have to attend school.
Not attending school with-out proper reason for example; sickness or a doctors visit, is illegal and is seen as wagging which is seen as fraud and punishable by law. Until the age of 12 children cannot be punished by law, but as soon as your child or you turn 12 years of age or older, you can be held responsible for wagging.
Punishments can be done as a fine, temporary jail time or a community service job done under supervision. Fines can be up to € 3 900 00.
These punishments can be given to the student and/or his or her legal parent or guardian.}}
{{SLA|Netherlands Antilles|15|12|2010?|}}
{{SLA|Norway|16|15|2009|}}
{{SLA|Northern Ireland|16|(15)|2014<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/know-when-you-can-leave-school|title=School leaving age - GOV.UK|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=2014-01-09|website=GOV.UK|publisher=Government Digital Service|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>|flag=no}}
{{SLA|Poland|15-18*|15|2002|After graduating from an 8-year [[primary school]] (usually at the age of 14 or 15) one can leave school but is legally required to continue education up to the age of 18. However, this requirement can be satisfied through vocational training, without attending a school. This can be done as a part of employment, so technically the person leaves a school and works full-time.}}
{{SLA|Portugal|18|16|2009|}}
